          "title": "The eschatological tyrant: self-deification and its terminus (vv. 36-45)",
          "body": "At verse 36 the chapter's language shifts register. The figure who emerges 'does as he pleases' in terms that exceed any single historical referent — he exalts himself above 'every god,' speaks 'monstrous things against the God of gods,' shows 'no regard for any god,' honors only military power as his deity (v. 38), and ultimately pitches his royal pavilion 'between the seas and the beautiful holy mountain' (v. 45). Whether vv. 36-45 describe Antiochus IV continuing under eschatological amplification, or a future Antichrist figure, is the chapter's most contested interpretive question. The historicist position (represented by commentators like John Calvin and E. J. Young) holds that vv. 36-45 remain Antiochan, with the details of vv. 40-45 not precisely matching any known campaign — which they attribute to the visionary's telescoping of history. The futurist-dispensational position (represented by Leon Wood, John Walvoord, and aligning with Revelation 13) argues that the details of vv. 36-45 go beyond anything Antiochus achieved, that Jesus's citation of 11:31 in Matthew 24:15 in a future-facing context implies a final fulfillment, and that 2 Thessalonians 2:3-4 (the 'man of lawlessness' who 'exalts himself above every so-called god') reflects the same portrait. Both positions hold the text's inerrancy; both are represented in the evangelical tradition. What neither position disputes is the chapter's final theological verdict: 'He will come to his end, and no one will help him' (v. 45). The tyrant who magnifies himself above every god ends without divine assistance, without human rescue, without ceremony. The appointed time arrives, and he is finished."
